UDF for creating directed graphs¶

In [5]:
# Creates a directed graph with weights using a numpay matrix as input. 
def create_directed_graph(mat):
    df = pd.DataFrame(mat)
    edges = get_edges(df)
    G = nx.DiGraph()
    G.add_nodes_from(range(0,len(df)))
    G.add_edges_from(edges)
    return G    

# Creates a list with all the edges where all entries are a tuple 
# containing the source node, head node and weigth of the node
def get_edges(df):
    n = len(df)
    l = []
    for i in range(0,n):
        for j in range(0,n):
            w = df[j][i]
            if w > 0:
                a = (i,j, {'weight':w})
                l.append(a)    
    return l

# Returns the eigenvecotor centrality of the lcc of the input df.
def get_eigenvector_centrality_lcc(df):
    (df, missing_names)= get_LCC(df)
    names_remain = list(df.index.values)
    temp_names = names_remain + missing_names
    m = df.as_matrix()
    (val, vec) = np.linalg.eig(np.transpose(m))
    
    
    eigenvector_centrality = list(np.abs(vec[:,0]).flatten())
    eigenvector_centrality= eigenvector_centrality+(list(np.zeros(len(missing_names))))
    df_T = pd.DataFrame(data = eigenvector_centrality, columns = ['Eigenvector Centrality'])
    df_T['Sector'] = temp_names
    return df_T

# return a df over the lcc of the input df as well.
# the names of those sectors that are not included in the largest connecting component.
def get_LCC(df):
    names = list(df.index.values)
    lcc = list(find_LCC(df))
    
    # This next part is only for us to get the names of the nodes we want to remove from the input df
    a = [x for x in range(lcc[0], lcc[-1] + 1)] 
    lcc = set(lcc)
    missing_i = list(lcc ^ set(a))
    missing_names = []
    for i in missing_i:
        temp = names[i]
        missing_names.append(temp)
    df = df.drop(index = missing_names, columns = missing_names) # Remove the nodes that are "missing" that is, those that are not in the lcc. 
    return df, missing_names

# Returns the index of the nodes that make up the largest connecting component. 
def find_LCC(df):
    temp_mat = df.as_matrix()
    temp_G = nx.from_numpy_matrix(temp_mat)
    return max(nx.connected_components(temp_G))

# All of these are rather self explainatory
def get_degree_centrality(df):
    in_degree_centrality = df.sum(axis=1)
    out_degree_centrality = df.sum(axis=0)    
    return in_degree_centrality, out_degree_centrality

def get_normalized_centrality(df, s):
    df = df.sort_values(ascending = False) / np.sum(df)
    df = pd.DataFrame(data=df)
    df = df.reset_index()
    df.index = df.index+1
    df.columns=['Sector',s]
    return df

def sort_centralities(df,s):
    df = df.sort_values(ascending = False)
    df = pd.DataFrame(data=df)
    df = df.reset_index()
    df.index = df.index+1
    df.columns=['Sector',s]
    return df

def merge(df1, df2):
    s = df1.columns[0]
    nd = df1.merge(df2, on=[s])
    return nd
  
# Get in and out degree centralities
def get_degree_centralities(df):
    (in_degree_centrality, out_degree_centrality) = get_degree_centrality(df)
    df_in_degree = sort_centralities(in_degree_centrality,'In degree Centralities')
    df_out_degree = sort_centralities(out_degree_centrality,'Out degree Centralities')
    degree_centrality = merge(df_in_degree, df_out_degree)
    return degree_centrality

# Get in and out degree centralities normalized
def get_degree_centralities_normalized(df):
    (in_degree_centrality, out_degree_centrality) = get_degree_centrality(df)
    in_degree_centrality_normalized = get_normalized_centrality(in_degree_centrality,'In Degree Centrality Normalized')
    out_degree_centrality_normalized = get_normalized_centrality(out_degree_centrality, 'Out Degree Centrality Normalized')
    degree_centrality = merge(in_degree_centrality_normalized, out_degree_centrality_normalized)
    return degree_centrality

# Returns the in-degree, out-degree and eigenvecotor centralities for a input df. norm is a boolean that if
# put to true normalizes the value before returning them. Retruns the df sorted by sector 
# based on in-degree-centrality.
def get_degree_eigen(df, norm = True):
    eigenvector_centrality = get_eigenvector_centrality_lcc(df)
    if norm is False:
        degree_centrality = get_degree_centralities(df)
    else:
        degree_centrality= get_degree_centralities_normalized(df)
        div = np.sum(list(eigenvector_centrality['Eigenvector Centrality']))
        eigenvector_centrality['Eigenvector Centrality'] = eigenvector_centrality['Eigenvector Centrality'] / div 
        eigenvector_centrality = eigenvector_centrality.rename(columns = {'Eigenvector Centrality': 'Eigenvector Centrality Normalized'})

    all_centralities = merge(degree_centrality, eigenvector_centrality)
    return all_centralities
In [1191]:
# Returns the Katz centrality. mu is assumed to be a uniform n*1 vector with the value 1 everywhere if we don't
# choose to assaign one on our own. 
def katz_centrality(G, beta=0.15, mu = 0, norm = False):
    
    if mu is 0:
        mu = np.ones((len(G), 1))
    return katz_centrality_helper(G, beta, mu, norm)

# For us to have default case for mu we use this helper function. 
def katz_centrality_helper(G, beta, mu, norm):
    adj_matrix = nx.to_numpy_matrix(G)
    lambda_w = np.round(np.real(max((np.linalg.eig(adj_matrix))[0])),0)
    alpha = (1-beta)/lambda_w
    katz = (np.linalg.inv(np.eye(len(adj_matrix)) -alpha *np.transpose(adj_matrix)).dot(mu)*beta).tolist()
    flat_list = [item for sublist in katz for item in sublist]
    if norm is True:
        div = sum(flat_list)
        flat_list = [x / div for x in flat_list]
    return flat_list

# Returns the katz centralities specified in the assaignment. 
def get_katz(df):
    mat = df.values
    G = create_directed_graph(mat)
    names = list(swemat.index.values)
    katz1 = katz_centrality(G, beta = 0.15)
    katz1_norm = katz_centrality(G, beta = 0.15, norm = True)
    
    # Wholesale entry is on the 30th row, we put that to one and all other entries in mu to zero. 
    mu = np.zeros((len(G), 1))
    mu[30,] = 1

    katz2 = katz_centrality(G, mu = mu, beta = 0.15)
    katz2_norm = katz_centrality(G, mu = mu, beta = 0.15, norm = True)

    katz = pd.DataFrame({'Sector': names, 'Katz Centrality': katz1, 'Katz Centrality, mu = [0...0 1 0...0]': katz2, 'Katz Centrality Normalized': katz1_norm, 'Katz Centrality, mu = [0...0 1 0...0] Normalized': katz2_norm})
    return katz

def print_top_centralities(mat,n=3,precision=3):
    
    # giving us a index of length n starting from 1, looks more neet
    i = list(range(1,n+1))
    
    # in, out and eigen 
    df = get_degree_eigen(mat)
    top_3_in = df[['Sector', 'In Degree Centrality Normalized']].sort_values(by=['In Degree Centrality Normalized'], ascending=False).head(n)
    top_3_in.index = i
    top_3_out = df[['Sector', 'Out Degree Centrality Normalized']].sort_values(by=['Out Degree Centrality Normalized'], ascending=False).head(n)
    top_3_out.index = i
    top_3_eig = df[['Sector', 'Eigenvector Centrality Normalized']].sort_values(by=['Eigenvector Centrality Normalized'], ascending=False).head(n)
    top_3_eig.index = i

    # Top Katz
    df = get_katz(mat)
    top_3_katz = df[['Sector', 'Katz Centrality Normalized']].sort_values(by=['Katz Centrality Normalized'], ascending=False).head(n)
    top_3_katz.index = i
    top_3_katz_mu = df[['Sector', 'Katz Centrality, mu = [0...0 1 0...0] Normalized']].sort_values(by=['Katz Centrality, mu = [0...0 1 0...0] Normalized'], ascending=False).head(n)
    top_3_katz_mu = top_3_katz_mu.rename(columns = {'Katz Centrality, mu = [0...0 1 0...0] Normalized': 'Katz Centrality Normalized'})
    top_3_katz_mu.index = i

    # Adjusting the pandas printout settings according to the input.
    pd.set_option('precision', precision)
    pd.set_option('colheader_justify', 'left')
    pd.set_option('display.max_colwidth', -1)
    
    #Prints 
    print('Three Most Central Secotrs According to the In-Degree Centrality')
    print(top_3_in)
    print('\n')

    print('Three Most Central Secotrs According to the Out-Degree Centrality')
    print(top_3_out)
    print('\n')

    print('Three Most Central Secotrs According to the Eigenvector Centrality')
    print(top_3_eig)
    print('\n')

    print('Three Most Central Secotrs According to the Katz Centrality')
    print(top_3_katz)
    print('\n')

    print('Three Most Central Secotrs According to the Katz Centrality With Non-Uniform mu')
    print(top_3_katz_mu)
    print('\n')

def pageRank(mat, beta=0.15, mu=0, tol=1e-06):
    n = mat.shape[0]  
    if mu is 0:
        mu = np.ones((n,1))
        print(len(mu))
    return pageRank_helper(mat, beta, mu, tol)

def pageRank_helper(mat, beta, mu, tol):
    sparse_matrix = sparse.csr_matrix(mat)
    P = normalize(sparse_matrix, axis=1, norm='l1')
    P_t = np.transpose(P)
    n = P_t.shape[0]
    z = np.zeros((n,1))
    Ps = (sparse.csr_matrix(np.eye(n)))
    k = 0
    dz = beta*mu
    z = z + dz
    while np.linalg.norm(dz) > tol:
        k = k+1
        Ps = P_t*Ps
        dz = beta*np.power((1-beta),k)*Ps*mu
        z = z + dz
    return list(np.squeeze(np.asarray(z)))

Discrete-time consensus algorithm with two stubborn nodes¶

UDFs¶

In [999]:
def average_dynamics(stubborn, u, P, niter=10):
    n = P[0].shape[1]
    # Get Reular Column
    regular = [*range(0,n)]
    for i in stubborn:
        regular.remove(i)
        
    # Get Q
    Q = P[regular, :][:, regular]
    E = P[regular, :][:, stubborn]
    
    x = np.zeros((n,niter))
    
    for i in range(0,len(stubborn)):
        x[stubborn[i]][0] = u[i]         
    
    for i in range(1,niter):
        x_reg = x[regular,i-1]
        x_reg = x_reg.reshape(-1,1)
        x_stub = x[stubborn,i-1]
        x_stub = x_stub.reshape(-1,1)
        a = Q.dot(x_reg).flatten('F') + E.dot(x_stub).flatten('F')
        x[regular,i] = a
        x[stubborn, i] = x[stubborn,i-1]
    #averaging_dynamics = x[:,-1].tolist()
    return x 

def pick_samples(df, df_r, n_1, n_2,Tot_rand =False):
    sample = []
    if Tot_rand is True:
        indexed = list(enumerate(df_r))
        bot = list([i for i, v in indexed])
        sample = rand.choices(bot, k=n_2)
    else:
        indexed = list(enumerate(df_r))
        top = sorted(indexed, key=operator.itemgetter(1))[-n_1:]
        bot = sorted(indexed, key=operator.itemgetter(1))[:n_1]
        top = list([i for i, v in top])
        bot = list([i for i, v in bot])
        sampling_top = rand.choices(top, k=n_2)
        sampling_bottom = rand.choices(bot, k=n_2)
        sample = sampling_top + sampling_bottom
    sample = list(set(sample + stubborn))
    return df[sample]

As can be seen in the the opinion distribution plots above, the mass of the probabilty moves to the right, the higher the pageRank the stubborn node with opinion 1 has. Analogously the mass of the probabilty "remains" to the left (remember that we initialize all the regular nodes to have opinion 0 here), the higher the pageRank the stubborn node with opinion 0 has.

This property is very nice to see as it is also rather intuative that a stubborn node is more successful to draw probability mass to their opinion if they have a high pageRank.

plt.figure(2, figsize = (12,5))
plt.plot(np.arange(0, 30), d_100_top_bot.transpose())
plt.title('The convergence of the 50 users with the most extreme opinon in both directions at t = 30 (100 in total)')

plt.figure(3, figsize = (12,5))
plt.plot(np.arange(0, 30), d_100_rand_top_bot.transpose())
plt.title('The Convergence of the 500 Users with the most extreme opinon in both directions at t = 30 (1000 in total)')

plt.show()

It is rather evident from these plots that a node with a higher pageRank is more successful at carrying out public opinion.

As can be seen in the the opinion distribution plots above, the mass of the probabilty moves to the right, the higher the pageRank the stubborn node with opinion 1 has. Analogously the mass of the probabilty "remains" to the left (remember that we initialize all the regular nodes to have opinion 0 here), the higher the pageRank the stubborn node with opinion 0 has.

This property is very nice to see as it is also rather intuative that a stubborn node is more successful to draw probability mass to their opinion if they have a high pageRank.
